<paragraph id="390236EBD054FFE9C18AFA78FD936009" blockId="6.[136,1452,1454,1553]" pageId="6" pageNumber="215">
Endemic to 
<collectingRegion id="FB79F809D054FFE9C00DFA78FEA263D1" box="[271,382,1454,1480]" country="Australia" name="Tasmania" pageId="6" pageNumber="215">Tasmania</collectingRegion>
. This lichenicolous species is most similar to the Australian species, 
<taxonomicName id="FEBD4D68D054FFE9C580FA79FB3763D1" box="[1154,1259,1455,1480]" class="Lecanoromycetes" family="Xylographaceae" genus="Lambiella" kingdom="Fungi" pageId="6" pageNumber="215" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="species" species="exigua">
<emphasis id="0BC9EAF9D054FFE9C580FA79FB3763D1" box="[1154,1259,1455,1480]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="215">L. exigua</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
* 
<superScript id="CEC89BA3D054FFE9C5FBFA78FAD563A5" attach="none" box="[1273,1289,1454,1468]" fontSize="6" pageId="6" pageNumber="215">1*</superScript>
, which differs by its non-lichenicolous habit and the absence of 
<emphasis id="0BC9EAF9D054FFE9C3A5FA04FCDB63F5" box="[679,775,1490,1516]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="215">sedifolia</emphasis>
-grey pigment in the epihymenium. The relationship between these two species deserves further study.
</paragraph>
